-- 
CANADA DAYBOOK: Bank of Canada Releases Monetary Policy Report

-- B y   S t e v e n   F r a n k
-- 
2011-04-13T04:10:10Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-13/canada-daybook-bank-of-canada-releases-monetary-policy-report.html
The  Bank of Canada  will elaborate
on yesterday’s interest-rate announcement with its monetary
policy report. Federal party leaders participate in the French-
language debate tonight.  WHAT TO WATCH:
*The four major party leaders prepare for the French-language
televised debate, following yesterday’s event in English, as
campaigning for the May 2 election continues.  ECONOMY:
*The Bank of  Canada  is scheduled to discuss its interest-rate
announcement in its monetary policy report to be published at
10:30 a.m. The document will detail the central bank’s new
forecasts for growth and inflation, and discuss the risks
surrounding its outlook. Governor Mark Carney and Senior Deputy
Governor Tiff Macklem will hold a press conference at 11:15 a.m.  EVENTS:
*Shaw Communications Inc., Canada’s largest cable and satellite
television provider by subscribers, is scheduled to report
second-quarter financial results in the morning, followed by a
conference call that can be accessed in Canada and the U.S. at
866-321-8231 or internationally at 416-642-5213. Passcode:
8631899.
*Executives of companies including European Goldfields Ltd.,
Centerra Gold Inc. and First Majestic Silver Corp. are scheduled
to address the Denver Gold Group  European Gold Forum  beginning
at 8 a.m. in Zurich.
*FirstService Corp., a property-services company, is scheduled
to hold its annual meeting at 4 p.m. in Toronto.
*Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce’s Renewable Energy & Clean
Technology Conference in Toronto, by invitation only.
* NovaGold Resources Inc. (NG) , which explores for gold in  Alaska  and
British Columbia, is scheduled to report first-quarter financial
results after markets close. A conference call will be held
tomorrow at 11:30 a.m. New York time that will be webcast at
 http://www.novagold.net  and can be accessed in  North America  at
866-212-4491 and internationally at 416-800-1066.  MARKETS:
*The S&P/TSX index lost 1.4 percent to 13,801.40, completing its
biggest two-day drop since June.
*Yields on two-year Government of Canada bonds fell 8 basis
points to 1.86 percent at 4:34 p.m. yesterday in Toronto.
*The Canadian dollar weakened 0.7 percent to 96.31 cents per  U.S.
dollar  at 4:34 p.m. yesterday. One Canadian dollar buys $1.0383.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Steven Frank in Toronto at 
 sfrank9@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Scanlan at   dscanlan@bloomberg.net . 